    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-10-25T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-10-25T08:00:00-05:00" n="180"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d180">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">841.74/10–2551: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Egypt</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d180fn1">Repeated to London, Paris for <persName
                            corresp="#p_MDII1">MacArthur</persName>, and Ankara.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <gloss target="#t_niact1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                        </gloss>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-10-25T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >October 25, 1951—3 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>568. <persName corresp="#p_SRC1">Stevenson</persName> was in despair last night.
                    Notwithstanding Gen <persName corresp="#p_RBH1">Robertson</persName>’s promise
                    to him in the morning he was threatening last night to turn off tap again
                    because he was not sure “Egypts had learned their lesson”. I took high exception
                    to this and <persName corresp="#p_SRC1">Stevenson</persName> promised to do his
                    best with Brit mil. “Remember, however,” he remarked, “We in England are without
                    a govt now”.<note n="2" xml:id="d180fn2">General elections were being held
                        throughout the United Kingdom on this day which led to a change of
                        governments, the Conservative Party led by <persName corresp="#p_CWL1"
                            >Winston Churchill</persName> replacing the Labour Party of <persName
                            corresp="#p_ACR1">Clement Attlee</persName>.</note> In addition to
                    formidable list consequence set out in <gloss target="#t_mytel1">mytel</gloss>
                    55 [<hi rend="italic">555</hi>]<note n="3" xml:id="d180fn3">Dated October 23,
                            <ref target="#pg_407">p. 407</ref>.</note> I should add important
                    irrigation pumps and domestic cooking. Furthermore, bakeries have fuel oil on
                    hand for about three days. What wld mobs do in dark streets?</p>
                <p>Brit Shell manager says cessation fuel oil traffic out of Suez wld force refinery
                    to close within two or three days owing lack storage facilities. This wld immed
                    force shut-down producing fields and deny white refinery products for pipeline
                    transport. Supplies thus lost wld be irremedial inasmuch as transport capacity
                    normally worked at maximum.</p>
                <p>Brit mil significantly have informed <persName corresp="#p_SRC1"
                        >Stevenson</persName> that their position in Canal Zone is untenable unless
                    they receive minimum coop from Egypts. I retorted, “That is not the way to get
                        it”.<note n="4" xml:id="d180fn4">In telegram 569 from Cairo, October 25,
                            <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">Caffery</persName> reported that <persName
                            corresp="#p_SRC1">Stevenson</persName> was able to persuade the British
                        military not to turn off the oil taps again “and he is proceeding to Suez
                        tomorrow to talk to <persName corresp="#p_RBH1">Robertson</persName> and
                        endeavor to persuade him that decision of that category shld be on cabinet
                        level.” <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">Caffery</persName> added that <persName
                            corresp="#p_SRC1">Stevenson</persName> was cabling London “to put
                        whatever govt comes in as result of elections on notice that very grave
                        decisions must be taken soon at London.” (641.74/10–2551)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
